 What are the four pillars of OOP?
âœ… Answer:

Encapsulation â€“ Hiding data using access modifiers (public, private, protected).
Abstraction â€“ Hiding implementation details and showing only the necessary functionality.
Inheritance â€“ Allowing one class to inherit the properties and methods of another.
Polymorphism â€“ Allowing methods to have different behaviors based on the object.



<?php
// **Encapsulation** â€“ Hiding data using access modifiers (public, private, protected)
class Vehicle {
    protected $brand;  // Protected property, accessible in child classes

    public function __construct($brand) {
        $this->brand = $brand;
    }

    // Getter method (Encapsulation)
    public function getBrand() {
        return $this->brand;
    }
}

// **Abstraction** â€“ Hiding implementation details and showing only necessary functionality
abstract class Car extends Vehicle {
    protected $model;

    public function __construct($brand, $model) {
        parent::__construct($brand);
        $this->model = $model;
    }

    abstract public function getCarInfo(); // Abstract method (must be implemented in child classes)
}

// **Inheritance** â€“ Allowing one class to inherit properties and methods of another
class Sedan extends Car {
    private $topSpeed;

    public function __construct($brand, $model, $topSpeed) {
        parent::__construct($brand, $model);
        $this->topSpeed = $topSpeed;
    }

    // Implementing abstract method (Abstraction)
    public function getCarInfo() {
        return "Brand: " . $this->brand . ", Model: " . $this->model . ", Top Speed: " . $this->topSpeed . " km/h";
    }
}

// **Polymorphism** â€“ Allowing methods to have different behaviors based on the object
class SUV extends Car {
    private $groundClearance;

    public function __construct($brand, $model, $groundClearance) {
        parent::__construct($brand, $model);
        $this->groundClearance = $groundClearance;
    }

    // Different implementation of getCarInfo (Polymorphism)
    public function getCarInfo() {
        return "Brand: " . $this->brand . ", Model: " . $this->model . ", Ground Clearance: " . $this->groundClearance . " mm";
    }
}

// Creating objects
$sedan = new Sedan("Toyota", "Camry", 240);
$suv = new SUV("Jeep", "Wrangler", 220);

// Displaying details (Polymorphism in action)
echo $sedan->getCarInfo() . "\n"; // Outputs: Brand: Toyota, Model: Camry, Top Speed: 240 km/h
echo $suv->getCarInfo() . "\n";   // Outputs: Brand: Jeep, Model: Wrangler, Ground Clearance: 220 mm
?>


What is a constructor in PHP OOP?
âœ… Answer:
A constructor (__construct) is a special method that is automatically called when an object is created. It is used to initialize properties.

class Person {
    public $name;

    public function __construct($name) {
        $this->name = $name;
    }
}
$person1 = new Person("John");
echo $person1->name; // Output: John


What are access modifiers in PHP OOP?
âœ… Answer:
Access modifiers control the visibility of properties and methods in a class:

public â†’ Accessible from anywhere.
private â†’ Accessible only within the class.
protected â†’ Accessible within the class and its child classes.

What is method overriding in PHP OOP?
âœ… Answer:
Method overriding occurs when a child class redefines a method inherited from the parent class.

class ParentClass {
    public function show() {
        return "Parent Method";
    }
}
class ChildClass extends ParentClass {
    public function show() {
        return "Child Method";
    }
}
$obj = new ChildClass();
echo $obj->show(); // Output: Child Method


What is method overloading in PHP?
âœ… Answer:
PHP does not support true method overloading, but it can be simulated using magic methods (__call).

ðŸ”¹ Example:
class Test {
    public function __call($name, $arguments) {
        return "Method $name does not exist!";
    }
}
$obj = new Test();
echo $obj->someMethod(); // Output: Method someMethod does not exist!


What is an interface in PHP OOP?
âœ… Answer:
An interface defines methods that a class must implement, but does not provide implementation itself.

ðŸ”¹ Example:
interface Animal {
    public function makeSound();
}
class Dog implements Animal {
    public function makeSound() {
        return "Bark";
    }
}
$dog = new Dog();
echo $dog->makeSound(); // Output: Bark

What is aggregation and association in OOP?
âœ… Answer:

Association: Two classes are related but independent.
Aggregation: One class owns another but both can exist independently.
Composition: One class fully depends on another.
